00:00:25.315 --> 00:00:26.690
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Today, we're

00:00:26.690 --> 00:00:30.900
doing electric power
systems, sort of as they are,

00:00:30.900 --> 00:00:32.060
and as they have been.

00:00:32.060 --> 00:00:36.290
In 2010, electric power
systems were about 40%--

00:00:36.290 --> 00:00:38.540
I'm going to have to stand
here and use the keyboard--

00:00:38.540 --> 00:00:45.860
about 40% of primary energy, and
40% of CO2 emissions, roughly.

00:00:45.860 --> 00:00:48.650
Most electricity goes to
residential and commercial

00:00:48.650 --> 00:00:54.890
sectors and supplies about
46% of the energy they use.

00:00:54.890 --> 00:00:56.990
What I want to do
today is to talk

00:00:56.990 --> 00:00:59.120
about the essential
features of these systems.

00:00:59.120 --> 00:01:02.720
I'm guessing most of you haven't
had a course in power systems

00:01:02.720 --> 00:01:05.690
since MIT doesn't teach a
course in power systems,

00:01:05.690 --> 00:01:11.810
really, and talk a little bit
about the regulatory regime.

00:01:11.810 --> 00:01:13.880
Monday we'll look
forward, what are

00:01:13.880 --> 00:01:16.970
some of the challenges, what are
some of the opportunities, what

00:01:16.970 --> 00:01:19.080
are some of the policy issues?

00:01:19.080 --> 00:01:22.290
So let's talk about
the power system.

00:01:22.290 --> 00:01:24.800
The one thing you really
do have to keep in mind

00:01:24.800 --> 00:01:27.290
is despite all of the
interest in storage,

00:01:27.290 --> 00:01:30.410
and everybody talks about
storage of electricity.

00:01:30.410 --> 00:01:32.240
As a practical
matter, you simply

00:01:32.240 --> 00:01:37.760
can't store electricity in
bulk at a reasonable cost.

00:01:37.760 --> 00:01:41.450
You can pump water uphill and
use pumped hydro, and that's

00:01:41.450 --> 00:01:43.440
pretty good, that's
pretty efficient,

00:01:43.440 --> 00:01:48.260
it's very hard to build
new pump hydro sites.

00:01:48.260 --> 00:01:49.640
There's one in New England.

00:01:49.640 --> 00:01:51.600
There are no plans
for any others.

00:01:51.600 --> 00:01:54.080
And as we'll see next
time, the value of storage

00:01:54.080 --> 00:01:56.250
goes up over time.

00:01:56.250 --> 00:01:58.880
You can also pump
air underground.

00:01:58.880 --> 00:02:02.610
And there are like two
of those in the world.

00:02:02.610 --> 00:02:04.640
And there's a lot of
research into batteries,

00:02:04.640 --> 00:02:06.980
but so far nothing looks cheap.

00:02:06.980 --> 00:02:11.840
So at the moment, the
system operates effectively

00:02:11.840 --> 00:02:14.540
without storage.

00:02:14.540 --> 00:02:16.850
And this matters
because demand varies

00:02:16.850 --> 00:02:20.430
over time in ways that
are perfectly predictable.

00:02:20.430 --> 00:02:23.190
Here's some seasonal variation.

00:02:23.190 --> 00:02:28.640
This is a forecast
for New England.

00:02:28.640 --> 00:02:33.770
And you'll see that as it says,
their week 8 is late July.

00:02:33.770 --> 00:02:36.420
Week 8 was forecast
to be the peak.

00:02:36.420 --> 00:02:39.530
And week 32, which is that
sort of secondary peak

00:02:39.530 --> 00:02:41.390
is early January.

00:02:41.390 --> 00:02:44.000
Most American systems
now look like that.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:47.390
They peak in the summertime,
that's air conditioning.

00:02:47.390 --> 00:02:49.260
There's also a good
deal of variation.

00:02:49.260 --> 00:02:50.660
So you have to follow that load.

00:02:50.660 --> 00:02:54.320
You have to follow that
variation in demand.

00:02:54.320 --> 00:02:57.620
But hour-by-hour, there's
a lot of variation.

