00:03:12.890 --> 00:03:18.620
And you'll see first of all
that the load in this relatively

00:03:18.620 --> 00:03:24.140
uneventful April week varied
within a day between 9,000

00:03:24.140 --> 00:03:28.200
and just about 16,000 megawatts.

00:03:28.200 --> 00:03:31.500
That's fairly substantial.

00:03:31.500 --> 00:03:35.490
You see April 2nd was a Monday.

00:03:35.490 --> 00:03:37.650
So you can see demand is
higher during the week

00:03:37.650 --> 00:03:41.120
than the last two
which are the weekends.

00:03:41.120 --> 00:03:43.820
You'll also see the
distinctive feature.

00:03:43.820 --> 00:03:47.480
There's sort of a morning peak
and an evening peak most days.

00:03:47.480 --> 00:03:52.340
The evening peak, again focus
on the actual load, the blue.

00:03:52.340 --> 00:03:55.370
The evening peak is the higher.

00:03:55.370 --> 00:03:58.100
And the minimum occurs in
the middle of the night,

00:03:58.100 --> 00:03:59.660
not too surprisingly.

00:03:59.660 --> 00:04:02.450
But the system
has to track that.

00:04:02.450 --> 00:04:04.400
The system has to track that.

00:04:04.400 --> 00:04:08.690
The other thing you will see
in terms of predictability,

00:04:08.690 --> 00:04:13.190
forecast load, I'm not sure
how far ahead that forecast is.

00:04:13.190 --> 00:04:16.040
But DA is Day Ahead.

00:04:16.040 --> 00:04:19.010
So the New England system
operates with a market.

00:04:19.010 --> 00:04:20.570
And there's a real
time clearing,

00:04:20.570 --> 00:04:22.153
which there has to
be because you have

00:04:22.153 --> 00:04:23.600
to follow it second-to-second.

00:04:23.600 --> 00:04:26.190
But there's also a
day ahead market.

00:04:26.190 --> 00:04:33.140
So the DA gives you in effect
the day ahead forecast.

00:04:33.140 --> 00:04:35.420
And you will see the
difference between the green

00:04:35.420 --> 00:04:41.900
and the blue is usually
small but not trivial, not 0.

