00:08:41.450 --> 00:08:44.840
turned on your computer, so OK.

00:08:48.910 --> 00:08:59.010
Short term variation, minute to
minute, the frequency, right?

00:08:59.010 --> 00:09:04.080
Everything assumes, all
your equipment assumes,

00:09:04.080 --> 00:09:06.120
your appliances
assume that you'll

00:09:06.120 --> 00:09:10.980
be getting electricity that
vary 60 cycles a second.

00:09:10.980 --> 00:09:13.530
That frequency has
to be maintained.

00:09:13.530 --> 00:09:17.070
And it's mainly maintained
by sort of automatic control

00:09:17.070 --> 00:09:18.430
at designated units.

00:09:18.430 --> 00:09:20.790
But when you get big
changes like that,

00:09:20.790 --> 00:09:22.710
governors aren't going to do it.

00:09:22.710 --> 00:09:26.160
And you will need to
bring units on and off.

00:09:26.160 --> 00:09:32.040
So let me talk about
technology mix.

00:09:32.040 --> 00:09:37.730
So we mentioned a little
earlier that you have fast

00:09:37.730 --> 00:09:42.620
responding generating
units, turbines say,

00:09:42.620 --> 00:09:47.210
or diesels to respond to
short term variations in load.

00:09:47.210 --> 00:09:51.110
But even if you could
forecast the load,

00:09:51.110 --> 00:09:54.190
you would want units like that.

00:09:54.190 --> 00:10:02.940
And as I mentioned, it's
expensive to vary the output

00:10:02.940 --> 00:10:05.340
from what are called base
load units, nuclear power

00:10:05.340 --> 00:10:08.320
plants, big coal plants.

00:10:08.320 --> 00:10:11.620
But not only that, when
you run them flat out,

00:10:11.620 --> 00:10:16.030
they have very low running
cost, nuclear virtually 0,

00:10:16.030 --> 00:10:19.090
coal pretty low.

00:10:19.090 --> 00:10:22.670
You can buy turbines or diesels.

00:10:22.670 --> 00:10:25.400
But they're very expensive
to build these big units.

00:10:25.400 --> 00:10:28.880
The little units, peaking
units or intermediate units,

00:10:28.880 --> 00:10:30.680
but let me just
assume two kinds,

00:10:30.680 --> 00:10:33.500
think coal plants
and gas turbines,

00:10:33.500 --> 00:10:35.960
they're cheap to
build, but they're

00:10:35.960 --> 00:10:40.340
expensive to run, relatively
on today's prices.

00:10:40.340 --> 00:10:45.560
So you would want
since load varies,

00:10:45.560 --> 00:10:48.330
you're not going to run your
whole fleet all the time,

00:10:48.330 --> 00:10:48.830
right?

00:10:48.830 --> 00:10:50.900
If we didn't have
those variations,

00:10:50.900 --> 00:10:54.230
if demand were constant,
you just build,

00:10:54.230 --> 00:10:56.180
well, but for
environmental issues

00:10:56.180 --> 00:10:58.070
you just build
cheap coal plants,

00:10:58.070 --> 00:11:01.970
cheap nuclear plants if you
could find one, combined cycle

00:11:01.970 --> 00:11:04.380
plants and run
them all the time.

00:11:04.380 --> 00:11:06.170
But since the load
varies, you know

00:11:06.170 --> 00:11:09.330
that you're not going to run
your plants all the time.

00:11:09.330 --> 00:11:10.640
So what do you do?

00:11:10.640 --> 00:11:17.120
If you look, Imagine two
plants of the same capacity.

00:11:17.120 --> 00:11:21.830
One is, I call it a peaker,
but let it be a gas turbine.

00:11:21.830 --> 00:11:26.057
And the other is a baseload,
let it be a coal plant.

00:11:26.057 --> 00:11:27.890
They don't tend to have
the same capacities,

00:11:27.890 --> 00:11:32.210
but for the sake of
argument, suppose they do.

00:11:32.210 --> 00:11:34.790
You ask, what's the
total cost of this plant?

00:11:38.341 --> 00:11:41.750
The more hours you
run it, the larger

00:11:41.750 --> 00:11:45.410
will be the fuel cost as a
component of total cost, right?

00:11:45.410 --> 00:11:48.020
So the total cost
consists of the cost

00:11:48.020 --> 00:11:51.800
of building the thing,
basically taken down

00:11:51.800 --> 00:11:54.920
to say a per day cost
or a per year cost.

00:11:54.920 --> 00:11:58.590
And then the slope is the
marginal cost of running it.

00:11:58.590 --> 00:12:01.340
So the height gives
you the total cost.

00:12:01.340 --> 00:12:04.520
If you're going to
run all year long,

00:12:04.520 --> 00:12:08.680
then the base load plant
is the plant to build.

00:12:08.680 --> 00:12:14.440
Because way out here, the
fact that the fuel is cheap

00:12:14.440 --> 00:12:17.260
makes up for the capital cost.

00:12:17.260 --> 00:12:19.240
But if you're only going
to run it a little bit

00:12:19.240 --> 00:12:20.980
but you have to
have it, then you

00:12:20.980 --> 00:12:24.910
want to build a peaker, right?

00:12:24.910 --> 00:12:26.790
Is that notion clear?

00:12:26.790 --> 00:12:28.680
The fact that there's
output variation

00:12:28.680 --> 00:12:31.470
means you want to have
plants of multiple types.

00:12:31.470 --> 00:12:33.840
If you can get a base
load plant to run

00:12:33.840 --> 00:12:38.790
almost all the time,
or all the time, then

00:12:38.790 --> 00:12:40.000
you're in great shape.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:41.730
But if you have to
have plants that

00:12:41.730 --> 00:12:45.780
run only a little bit,
only a few hours per year,

00:12:45.780 --> 00:12:48.090
then you've got to
have some of these.

00:12:48.090 --> 00:12:50.590
And you've always got that mix.

00:12:50.590 --> 00:12:53.610
We're going to talk about
wind and solar next time.

00:12:53.610 --> 00:12:55.830
They don't quite fit
either of these categories,

00:12:55.830 --> 00:12:59.340
if you think about
it for a minute.

00:12:59.340 --> 00:13:03.676
But if that's clear,
then let's look at this.

00:13:07.148 --> 00:13:11.430
The red curve is what's
called a low duration curve.

00:13:11.430 --> 00:13:14.760
And it's the actual curve,
because I happen to find it.

00:13:14.760 --> 00:13:17.400
It's the actual curve for--

00:13:17.400 --> 00:13:18.750
it's probably England and Wales.

00:13:18.750 --> 00:13:22.980
It says Great Britain, for 2007.

00:13:22.980 --> 00:13:25.170
What a low duration
curve is, you

00:13:25.170 --> 00:13:30.810
look at how much electricity
was consumed hour-by-hour.

00:13:30.810 --> 00:13:35.490
And you basically convert those
to a graph putting the hour

00:13:35.490 --> 00:13:37.650
with the highest
consumption here, then

00:13:37.650 --> 00:13:39.060
the second highest there.

00:13:39.060 --> 00:13:41.700
You basically stack it up.

00:13:41.700 --> 00:13:47.340
So out here at 100%, you have
the consumption, the demand,

00:13:47.340 --> 00:13:49.260
and it's expressed as
a percentage of peak

00:13:49.260 --> 00:13:56.310
to keep life simple, the
percentage of peak demand

00:13:56.310 --> 00:14:00.840
at the lowest hour of the
year, presumably at 3 o'clock

00:14:00.840 --> 00:14:02.670
in the morning on
some day that was

00:14:02.670 --> 00:14:04.770
neither hot nor cold
so nobody needed

00:14:04.770 --> 00:14:07.290
to run anything, any HVAC.

00:14:07.290 --> 00:14:10.710
And it was a holiday, so there
was no industrial work going

00:14:10.710 --> 00:14:12.910
on, or whatever.

00:14:12.910 --> 00:14:17.790
So if you go back to this
picture, this picture says,

00:14:17.790 --> 00:14:22.582
if you're going to run a plant
fewer than H star hours a year,

00:14:22.582 --> 00:14:23.790
you're going to want to peak.

00:14:23.790 --> 00:14:25.560
It's going to have to be a peak.

00:14:25.560 --> 00:14:28.065
It should be a peaker
rather than a baseload.

00:14:31.200 --> 00:14:35.070
Come to this picture, and
you say, OK, let's suppose--

00:14:35.070 --> 00:14:37.170
just because it
fits the picture--

00:14:37.170 --> 00:14:41.110
that if there are
8,760 hours in a year,

00:14:41.110 --> 00:14:42.810
this is like 42
gallons in a barrel,

00:14:42.810 --> 00:14:44.910
another one of those
numbers you have to have.

00:14:44.910 --> 00:14:54.970
8,760 hours in a year,
let's see if I can do this.

00:14:54.970 --> 00:15:00.250
If you build baseload
capacity up to this line,

00:15:00.250 --> 00:15:04.810
you know that it will be
running at least that fraction

00:15:04.810 --> 00:15:05.770
of hours.

00:15:05.770 --> 00:15:07.930
You'll have to cut
it down somewhat

00:15:07.930 --> 00:15:11.680
in the really low hours.

00:15:11.680 --> 00:15:15.670
But if you build that
much baseload capacity,

00:15:15.670 --> 00:15:19.300
it will run for at
least this many hours.

00:15:19.300 --> 00:15:23.710
Because demand exceeds that
capacity for that fraction

00:15:23.710 --> 00:15:25.740
of the year, right?

00:15:25.740 --> 00:15:32.110
So we're asking,
you decide what you

00:15:32.110 --> 00:15:34.780
want to build in terms
of baseload capacity

00:15:34.780 --> 00:15:36.580
as a fraction of the peak.

00:15:36.580 --> 00:15:39.790
Read across to the
curve and come down

00:15:39.790 --> 00:15:43.240
and you get the fraction of
hours of the year when demand

00:15:43.240 --> 00:15:47.950
is at least that high, right?

00:15:47.950 --> 00:15:51.270
So we've normalized
the low duration curve

00:15:51.270 --> 00:15:52.840
so the peak is 100.

00:15:52.840 --> 00:15:55.870
We also normalized time,
which is kind of awkward

00:15:55.870 --> 00:16:00.590
so that 8,760 hours equals 100.

00:16:00.590 --> 00:16:04.100
So we can do percentages.

00:16:04.100 --> 00:16:07.300
So again, this is just stylized.

00:16:07.300 --> 00:16:11.620
But if H star over
8,760 is here,

00:16:11.620 --> 00:16:15.440
then that says you build half
baseload capacity and half

00:16:15.440 --> 00:16:17.650
peaker capacity, right?

00:16:17.650 --> 00:16:22.000
The peakers are only
going to come into play

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:24.890
when demand is above--

00:16:24.890 --> 00:16:26.410
and this is where
I need the laser--

00:16:26.410 --> 00:16:29.050
is above that 50% point.

00:16:29.050 --> 00:16:32.560
That's an artifact.

00:16:32.560 --> 00:16:33.880
This is stylized 50%.

00:16:33.880 --> 00:16:37.300
It has no particular
significance in life.

00:16:37.300 --> 00:16:39.530
It just works out
in this picture.

00:16:39.530 --> 00:16:43.190
So you'd build 1/2 peaker
capacity and 1/2 base load.

00:16:43.190 --> 00:16:50.920
The peak units would be on for
less than H star hours a year,

00:16:50.920 --> 00:16:55.392
or less than this fraction
of hours per year.

00:16:55.392 --> 00:16:56.350
So it makes some sense.

00:16:59.450 --> 00:17:01.790
You see why you need the mix.

00:17:01.790 --> 00:17:04.760
And this is just
mechanical to say,

00:17:04.760 --> 00:17:09.140
if I know where the breakpoint
is, then I've got to say,

00:17:09.140 --> 00:17:10.385
what fraction of the year.

00:17:14.010 --> 00:17:15.770
I've got to use the
low duration curve

00:17:15.770 --> 00:17:22.160
to go from the break
point where I decide

00:17:22.160 --> 00:17:24.290
between the different
technologies, the base

00:17:24.290 --> 00:17:27.560
load and the peaker
in this case,

00:17:27.560 --> 00:17:31.800
and to get a capacity mix out
of that, for what fraction

00:17:31.800 --> 00:17:34.770
of the year, blah, blah, blah.

00:17:34.770 --> 00:17:40.380
OK, I know I want to build
baseload plants that will

00:17:40.380 --> 00:17:42.925
run at least this fraction.

00:17:45.780 --> 00:17:49.110
We'll run at least this
fraction of the year.

00:17:49.110 --> 00:17:52.590
I want peakers
that will run less.

00:17:52.590 --> 00:17:57.390
The load duration curve
translates that into capacity,

00:17:57.390 --> 00:17:58.770
OK.

00:17:58.770 --> 00:18:02.670
Detail is not critical,
concept pretty critical.

00:18:02.670 --> 00:18:03.300
Questions?

00:18:07.030 --> 00:18:08.362
Yeah.

