00:18:18.010 --> 00:18:19.600
Where's the breakpoint?

00:18:19.600 --> 00:18:22.510
Where is the breakpoint?

00:18:22.510 --> 00:18:24.740
And then what I
would do in fact,

00:18:24.740 --> 00:18:27.550
if I'm doing this, if
I'm centrally planning

00:18:27.550 --> 00:18:32.380
and I'm not a market, if I'm
centrally planning I would A,

00:18:32.380 --> 00:18:35.030
allow for reserve margin.

00:18:35.030 --> 00:18:38.050
So I wouldn't build
just capacity.

00:18:38.050 --> 00:18:41.200
And I would allow for the fact
that I don't know the load

00:18:41.200 --> 00:18:43.660
duration curve exactly.

00:18:43.660 --> 00:18:46.900
So I'd do a little
stochastic work here.

00:18:46.900 --> 00:18:50.960
I'd say, if the curve
varies up and down by 20%,

00:18:50.960 --> 00:18:52.720
what do I need to be sure?

00:18:52.720 --> 00:18:56.110
And I'd work out a somewhat
more complicated problem.

00:18:56.110 --> 00:19:01.450
What I gave you was, well, if
I've only got two technologies

00:19:01.450 --> 00:19:06.130
and the slate is
clean, then I know

00:19:06.130 --> 00:19:11.320
how to choose based on how
long the plant is going to run.

00:19:11.320 --> 00:19:16.540
And using this curve, I can
go from how long the plant is

00:19:16.540 --> 00:19:20.550
going to run to how
much of it I need,

00:19:20.550 --> 00:19:23.370
based on how many
hours demand will

00:19:23.370 --> 00:19:26.940
be above and below
certain levels, right?

00:19:26.940 --> 00:19:29.700
So yeah, that's exactly what
this exercise in the very

00:19:29.700 --> 00:19:30.780
simple case would do.

00:19:30.780 --> 00:19:33.160
It would optimize the fleet.

00:19:33.160 --> 00:19:34.820
And you need both.

00:19:34.820 --> 00:19:38.590
Even if you don't have to worry
about quick response, which

00:19:38.590 --> 00:19:45.310
is not present in this
picture, you'd need both, OK.

00:19:51.430 --> 00:19:54.790
In fact, in real systems you
have multiple technologies.

00:19:54.790 --> 00:19:59.770
And this is a very strange
graph, but it makes that point.

00:19:59.770 --> 00:20:07.030
This shows in 2008
supposedly ranked vertically

00:20:07.030 --> 00:20:10.630
by marginal cost
