00:20:17.320 --> 00:20:22.420
And so it gives you
sort of a supply curve.

00:20:22.420 --> 00:20:24.950
The lower 48 states are
not a single market.

00:20:24.950 --> 00:20:27.190
So it's a funny kind
of supply curve.

00:20:27.190 --> 00:20:29.050
But it gives you the sense.

00:20:29.050 --> 00:20:38.020
It shows hydro there in the
far left, which essentially, it

00:20:38.020 --> 00:20:40.775
has only an opportunity
cost of running, right?

00:20:40.775 --> 00:20:43.150
If you let the water out now,
you don't have it tomorrow.

00:20:43.150 --> 00:20:45.108
So there's a little bit
of an opportunity cost.

00:20:45.108 --> 00:20:46.930
But out of pocket is 0.

00:20:46.930 --> 00:20:50.860
And then you've got nukes, which
have a very low running cost.

00:20:50.860 --> 00:20:55.670
And then you've got this mixture
of coal and gas and others.

00:20:55.670 --> 00:21:00.520
And then finally, up here
that vertical portion,

00:21:00.520 --> 00:21:03.640
that's the oh, my God,
start the diesels portion.

00:21:03.640 --> 00:21:06.850
That's the very hot summer day
when very inefficient, very

00:21:06.850 --> 00:21:08.450
dirty diesels that
are kept around

00:21:08.450 --> 00:21:12.740
to run for only a few
hours a year get fired up.

00:21:12.740 --> 00:21:14.650
So there are really
expensive units

00:21:14.650 --> 00:21:17.640
that you keep on hand,
even though they're

00:21:17.640 --> 00:21:20.280
expensive to run
because you've got them.

00:21:20.280 --> 00:21:23.110
And on a hot summer
day, you may need them.

00:21:23.110 --> 00:21:25.800
So in fact, that two
technology picture

00:21:25.800 --> 00:21:30.540
that I gave you is too simple
because you'd want to build

00:21:30.540 --> 00:21:32.730
a more complicated mixture.

00:21:32.730 --> 00:21:37.430
But you need a mixture, OK.

00:21:37.430 --> 00:21:40.170
Comments, yeah, Scott.

00:21:40.170 --> 00:21:42.170
AUDIENCE: So by
capacity, does it mean

00:21:42.170 --> 00:21:44.160
what capacity you turn it on?

