the total hydro capacity.

00:21:48.720 --> 00:21:51.820
This is the total nuclear
capacity, this distance.

00:21:51.820 --> 00:21:54.810
So it's giving you a sense
of how much you can get

00:21:54.810 --> 00:21:56.820
at different marginal costs.

00:21:56.820 --> 00:22:00.030
So it is a supply
curve in that sense

00:22:00.030 --> 00:22:03.230
if they were all in the same
market dot, dot, dot, dot,

00:22:03.230 --> 00:22:07.090
yeah, OK.

00:22:10.870 --> 00:22:12.760
OK, what's the grid look like?

00:22:18.070 --> 00:22:19.870
You can have multiple
generating plants

00:22:19.870 --> 00:22:22.180
in any particular region.

00:22:22.180 --> 00:22:25.330
But you really
can't economically

00:22:25.330 --> 00:22:27.910
have multiple
transmission systems

00:22:27.910 --> 00:22:30.400
and multiple
distribution systems.

00:22:30.400 --> 00:22:35.950
They are typically considered
natural monopolies.

00:22:35.950 --> 00:22:39.460
What a natural monopoly
means is generally

00:22:39.460 --> 00:22:45.920
defined as having more than
one of them would raise costs.

00:22:45.920 --> 00:22:51.820
So if you think of the X's
in that subadditivity bullet

00:22:51.820 --> 00:22:56.890
as basically electricity
supplied to houses,

00:22:56.890 --> 00:23:01.990
so each component is
a house or a building,

00:23:01.990 --> 00:23:04.690
rather than total kilowatt
hours, but a vector

00:23:04.690 --> 00:23:08.830
of locations, then
subadditivity by that definition

00:23:08.830 --> 00:23:12.700
means it's cheaper to supply.

00:23:12.700 --> 00:23:18.400
You can't split the system
without raising costs.

00:23:18.400 --> 00:23:20.440
The normal picture
you get for this

00:23:20.440 --> 00:23:30.480
is, if the X's are scalars, then
it's just economies of scale.

00:23:30.480 --> 00:23:36.420
So natural monopoly is
present in electricity.

00:23:36.420 --> 00:23:42.100
It's present in
other areas as well.

00:23:42.100 --> 00:23:45.303
Let's do a minute on why
there's a problem when

00:23:45.303 --> 00:23:46.470
you have a natural monopoly.

00:23:46.470 --> 00:23:47.870
What's the policy problem?

00:23:54.140 --> 00:23:56.740
Why do we bother
to talk about it?

00:23:56.740 --> 00:23:58.150
Alex, are you raising your hand?

00:23:58.150 --> 00:24:00.010
Or no, you were not
raising your hand.

00:24:00.010 --> 00:24:01.840
You were thinking about
raising your hand?

00:24:01.840 --> 00:24:02.710
No, not even that.

00:24:02.710 --> 00:24:10.260
OK, OK, we're back
in 1401 or 001.

00:24:10.260 --> 00:24:11.710
Kierstan and then David.

00:24:11.710 --> 00:24:15.967
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
otherwise a natural monopoly

00:24:15.967 --> 00:24:20.500
would release them to just
take as much as they could.

00:24:20.500 --> 00:24:22.000
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
So what enables

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:23.740
it to take as much as it could?

00:24:23.740 --> 00:24:25.000
AUDIENCE: No competition.

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:26.375
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
So you think

00:24:26.375 --> 00:24:37.260
there would be no competition
and they'd make a lot of money.

00:24:37.260 --> 00:24:41.820
But we like making a
lot of money, don't we?

00:24:41.820 --> 00:24:42.570
Consumers don't.

00:24:42.570 --> 00:24:45.090
So there'd be a welfare loss.

00:24:50.960 --> 00:24:52.820
David?

00:24:52.820 --> 00:24:55.220
AUDIENCE: I mean, yeah, they
could just charge as much

00:24:55.220 --> 00:25:01.400
up to the point where it would
be profitable for another firm

00:25:01.400 --> 00:25:02.690
to enter.

00:25:02.690 --> 00:25:04.982
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: I mean,
it's actually interesting.

00:25:04.982 --> 00:25:07.670
We always assume in
these discussions

00:25:07.670 --> 00:25:08.960
that competition isn't viable.

00:25:11.470 --> 00:25:14.050
And cable television
is a standard example

00:25:14.050 --> 00:25:16.702
of a natural monopoly, local
cable television distribution.

00:25:16.702 --> 00:25:18.535
But there are a number
of places where there

00:25:18.535 --> 00:25:21.250
are competing cable systems.

00:25:21.250 --> 00:25:25.180
And that's wasteful, but it may
be less wasteful than having

00:25:25.180 --> 00:25:26.880
really high prices--

00:25:26.880 --> 00:25:31.311
welfare loss because
of high prices.

00:25:31.311 --> 00:25:32.907
AUDIENCE: They can
also under supply.

00:25:32.907 --> 00:25:35.240
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Well,
that's the same story, right?

00:25:35.240 --> 00:25:36.290
You raise the price.

00:25:36.290 --> 00:25:39.560
You supply less.

00:25:39.560 --> 00:25:40.400
I can't draw it.

00:25:40.400 --> 00:25:45.170
You might like to end
up at some point like A,

00:25:45.170 --> 00:25:50.180
and in fact, what a monopoly
in this situation might do

00:25:50.180 --> 00:25:53.420
is produce 1/2 that where
the production would B,

00:25:53.420 --> 00:25:56.800
but the price would be
notably higher than at A.

00:25:56.800 --> 00:25:58.550
AUDIENCE: That's good
for the environment.

00:25:58.550 --> 00:25:58.880
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: What?

00:25:58.880 --> 00:26:01.530
AUDIENCE: It's good for the
environment [INAUDIBLE],,

00:26:01.530 --> 00:26:03.447
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Good for the environment.

00:26:03.447 --> 00:26:04.620
Good for the environment.

00:26:04.620 --> 00:26:06.930
So we should just
deregulate electricity

00:26:06.930 --> 00:26:11.550
throughout because we'd
spent a lot of money.

00:26:11.550 --> 00:26:12.892
Interesting point.

00:26:12.892 --> 00:26:14.850
Anybody else, anything
else that could go wrong

00:26:14.850 --> 00:26:15.680
in this situation?

00:26:19.570 --> 00:26:22.590
OK, what about cost?

00:26:22.590 --> 00:26:26.100
Let's think about human beings
running an organization.

00:26:26.100 --> 00:26:29.130
And you have no competition.

00:26:29.130 --> 00:26:32.470
And you're providing
a necessity.

00:26:32.470 --> 00:26:36.520
And your brother-in-law
asks for a job.

00:26:36.520 --> 00:26:39.340
You hire your
brother-in-law, right?

00:26:39.340 --> 00:26:40.645
There's a cost problem.

00:26:45.060 --> 00:26:50.970
We always draw these curves
like these come out of the sky.

00:26:50.970 --> 00:26:52.770
And we march down cost curves.

00:26:52.770 --> 00:26:56.730
In fact, these are determined
by organizational decisions.

00:26:56.730 --> 00:27:01.230
And when you have a monopoly,
the pressure to actually do

00:27:01.230 --> 00:27:05.850
unpleasant things like
firing people or not

00:27:05.850 --> 00:27:11.130
hiring your brother-in-law,
those pressures are gone.

00:27:11.130 --> 00:27:13.650
Not gone, they're diminished.

00:27:13.650 --> 00:27:14.610
They're diminished.

00:27:14.610 --> 00:27:15.705
So you expect high costs.

00:27:19.780 --> 00:27:22.540
There's another
reason, and it's not

00:27:22.540 --> 00:27:25.100
true for all natural monopolies.

00:27:25.100 --> 00:27:29.050
But it's true for the ones that
we're mostly concerned about,

00:27:29.050 --> 00:27:31.760
most of these things are
called public utilities.

00:27:31.760 --> 00:27:36.110
Now, it's not true for
cable television yet.

00:27:36.110 --> 00:27:38.200
Electricity used to
be a luxury good.

00:27:38.200 --> 00:27:39.820
Telephones used to
be a luxury good.

00:27:39.820 --> 00:27:41.650
They're not anymore.

00:27:41.650 --> 00:27:44.410
They're mostly
considered necessities.

00:27:44.410 --> 00:27:47.680
And when you raise the price,
as Kierstan wanted them to do,

00:27:47.680 --> 00:27:50.740
to raise the price to
pay for necessities,

00:27:50.740 --> 00:27:53.620
you're basically taking money
out of poor people's pockets

00:27:53.620 --> 00:27:56.600
and giving them to
rich shareholders.

00:27:56.600 --> 00:28:02.290
So these are the problems that
people mostly worry about.

00:28:02.290 --> 00:28:04.840
And that business about
triangles and rectangles,

00:28:04.840 --> 00:28:05.890
let me just remind you.

00:28:13.230 --> 00:28:15.450
For some reason let
this be marginal cost

00:28:15.450 --> 00:28:18.400
equals average cost.

00:28:18.400 --> 00:28:22.450
And this is the demand curve.

00:28:22.450 --> 00:28:26.273
And this is, of course,
what you'd like, right?

00:28:26.273 --> 00:28:27.690
You'd like production
at the point

00:28:27.690 --> 00:28:30.700
where price equals
marginal cost.

00:28:30.700 --> 00:28:35.240
And this is the price axis,
and this is the quantity axis.

00:28:35.240 --> 00:28:37.760
The classic thing that
a monopoly might do

00:28:37.760 --> 00:28:43.010
is to produce say,
QM, and charge PM.

00:28:46.170 --> 00:28:50.040
And then the deadweight loss,
this triangle over here.

00:28:50.040 --> 00:28:52.440
I'm hoping, I'm
reminding you, it's

00:28:52.440 --> 00:28:55.980
the difference between what
people were willing to pay

00:28:55.980 --> 00:28:59.130
and what it would have cost
to produce this output that's

00:28:59.130 --> 00:29:01.080
not produced.

00:29:01.080 --> 00:29:02.250
So that's a loss, right?

00:29:02.250 --> 00:29:07.980
If you reduce output
from say Q star to QM,

00:29:07.980 --> 00:29:11.050
you lose that triangle.

00:29:11.050 --> 00:29:13.180
But suppose what
in fact, happens

00:29:13.180 --> 00:29:22.090
is the monopolist is really
lazy and costs go up to PM.

00:29:22.090 --> 00:29:26.830
Well, in that case, you
lose the rectangle too.

00:29:26.830 --> 00:29:29.440
And in most reasonable
cases, the rectangles

00:29:29.440 --> 00:29:32.090
are bigger than the triangles.

00:29:32.090 --> 00:29:34.600
So that if I can't resist
hiring my brother-in-law,

00:29:34.600 --> 00:29:35.740
neither can anybody else.

00:29:35.740 --> 00:29:41.320
That could be much worse aside
from the rich/poor issue,

00:29:41.320 --> 00:29:44.950
than the fact that
I'm pricing high, OK.

00:29:44.950 --> 00:29:46.450
So these are things
you worry about.

00:29:50.970 --> 00:29:53.840
What do you do about it?

00:29:53.840 --> 00:29:55.370
Water supply is like this.

00:29:55.370 --> 00:29:57.410
You could argue bus
service is like this.

00:29:57.410 --> 00:29:59.360
Telephone distribution
is like this.

00:29:59.360 --> 00:30:01.820
Electricity distribution
is like this.

00:30:01.820 --> 00:30:03.738
Electricity transmission
is like this.

00:30:03.738 --> 00:30:05.030
Now, we're mostly about energy.

00:30:05.030 --> 00:30:07.230
But it is a general problem.

00:30:07.230 --> 00:30:09.890
What are some of the
solutions, right.

00:30:09.890 --> 00:30:15.490
This difficulty,
a natural monopoly

00:30:15.490 --> 00:30:19.510
arises across time and
space and industries.

00:30:19.510 --> 00:30:24.670
And a variety of mechanisms
have been adopted.

00:30:24.670 --> 00:30:25.720
What might you do?

00:30:34.890 --> 00:30:43.910
So we could have a private firm,
and we could regulate it, OK?

00:30:43.910 --> 00:30:46.090
Anything else, Brendan?

00:30:46.090 --> 00:30:51.598
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:30:51.598 --> 00:30:53.390
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Well, that's not good.

00:30:53.390 --> 00:30:54.307
What am I going to do?

00:30:54.307 --> 00:30:57.170
If I can't have competition
as an economic matter.

00:30:57.170 --> 00:30:58.520
I can split it.

00:30:58.520 --> 00:31:01.010
You're saying
forced competition.

00:31:01.010 --> 00:31:04.220
Well, what if I split it
and in fact, one of them

00:31:04.220 --> 00:31:06.010
