00:31:06.010 --> 00:31:12.290
See, the problem with this, if
you go back to this picture,

00:31:12.290 --> 00:31:13.730
if I've got two
firms and they're

00:31:13.730 --> 00:31:16.550
both on this cost
curve, the larger one

00:31:16.550 --> 00:31:19.290
always has a cost advantage.

00:31:19.290 --> 00:31:23.600
So you can imagine
competition working.

00:31:23.600 --> 00:31:26.330
But you could also imagine the
larger firm drives the smaller

00:31:26.330 --> 00:31:28.770
firm out just competing.

00:31:28.770 --> 00:31:31.410
And nobody comes in because
they have a big cost

00:31:31.410 --> 00:31:33.120
disadvantage if they come in.

00:31:33.120 --> 00:31:34.860
So that's a tough one.

00:31:34.860 --> 00:31:37.120
Most industries, that's
what you want to do.

00:31:37.120 --> 00:31:38.490
And that's what's done.

00:31:38.490 --> 00:31:40.520
But that's tough here.

00:31:40.520 --> 00:31:41.720
Anything else?

00:31:41.720 --> 00:31:43.970
Yeah, Max.

00:31:43.970 --> 00:31:46.130
AUDIENCE: A government
run enterprise.

00:31:46.130 --> 00:31:53.930
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: You
