when I asked this question the
first year I taught the course,

00:45:07.640 --> 00:45:09.700
the answer from a Texan
was, so we can secede.

00:45:12.968 --> 00:45:15.260
I don't know why they wouldn't
take Amarillo with them.

00:45:15.260 --> 00:45:17.440
And whoever that
second dot is, I

00:45:17.440 --> 00:45:20.410
don't know who that is either.

00:45:20.410 --> 00:45:22.150
I don't have an answer.

00:45:22.150 --> 00:45:26.950
My guess is that actually
was an electrical response.

00:45:26.950 --> 00:45:30.760
That part of Texas may have had
closer electrical connections

00:45:30.760 --> 00:45:33.622
outside the state than inside.

00:45:33.622 --> 00:45:35.080
And somebody said,
look, that would

00:45:35.080 --> 00:45:38.380
be really stupid to kind of
reconfigure the transmission

00:45:38.380 --> 00:45:39.850
system.

00:45:39.850 --> 00:45:40.570
I'm guessing.

00:45:40.570 --> 00:45:42.250
I don't know.

00:45:42.250 --> 00:45:44.730
Anything else?

00:45:44.730 --> 00:45:52.870
OK, all right, let me spend
most of the rest of the time

00:45:52.870 --> 00:45:55.270
on sort of how we
got here and walk

00:45:55.270 --> 00:45:56.650
through the regulatory history.

00:46:01.100 --> 00:46:04.820
First, central generating
station, Thomas Edison,

00:46:04.820 --> 00:46:09.530
New York, 59
customers, lighting.

00:46:09.530 --> 00:46:14.120
And by the way, you think you
have a load variation problem

00:46:14.120 --> 00:46:16.230
now with those New
England things,

00:46:16.230 --> 00:46:19.980
think about when your
only product is lighting.

00:46:19.980 --> 00:46:23.480
You shut the whole system
down in the daytime.

00:46:23.480 --> 00:46:25.952
This is not a good way
to use your assets.

00:46:25.952 --> 00:46:27.410
So one of the first
things they did

00:46:27.410 --> 00:46:31.010
was push for
electric streetcars.

00:46:31.010 --> 00:46:33.470
These early systems,
direct current systems

00:46:33.470 --> 00:46:37.190
were regulated mostly by cities.

00:46:37.190 --> 00:46:38.188
They were local.

00:46:38.188 --> 00:46:39.230
They were direct current.

00:46:39.230 --> 00:46:41.090
Direct current at
low voltage doesn't

00:46:41.090 --> 00:46:43.792
travel very far efficiently.

00:46:43.792 --> 00:46:46.250
And you don't want to put high
voltage into people's homes.

00:46:48.780 --> 00:46:52.550
So we had a bunch
city-regulated systems

00:46:52.550 --> 00:46:55.650
and then we had a bunch
of city-run systems.

00:46:55.650 --> 00:46:58.380
So in 1900, as
far as I can tell,

00:46:58.380 --> 00:47:02.840
the peak of municipal
systems, Belmont has one,

00:47:02.840 --> 00:47:11.310
Los Angeles has one, they peaked
at 8% of generation in 1900.

00:47:11.310 --> 00:47:15.180
As alternating current
came in, and the big thing

00:47:15.180 --> 00:47:18.480
with alternating current is
you can change it's voltage

00:47:18.480 --> 00:47:19.640
relatively easily.

00:47:19.640 --> 00:47:22.530
So you can have high voltage
to send it long distances.

00:47:22.530 --> 00:47:25.420
And then you can take it
down for use in homes.

00:47:25.420 --> 00:47:32.700
So the transformer really makes
alternating current the winner.

00:47:32.700 --> 00:47:35.460
Now, You can take
DC up and down.

00:47:35.460 --> 00:47:37.140
But it's more expensive.

00:47:37.140 --> 00:47:39.670
And you couldn't do
it for a long time.

00:47:39.670 --> 00:47:41.490
So alternating current wins.

00:47:41.490 --> 00:47:46.740
And as you begin to make
it technically possible

00:47:46.740 --> 00:47:48.780
to go beyond a city--

00:47:48.780 --> 00:47:50.438
if you're doing
direct current, you're

00:47:50.438 --> 00:47:52.980
building a generating station,
you're serving a neighborhood.

00:47:52.980 --> 00:47:54.990
We talked about
the London system

00:47:54.990 --> 00:47:57.030
and how it stayed that
way for a long time.

00:47:57.030 --> 00:47:58.410
That's how they grow up.

00:47:58.410 --> 00:48:00.610
You build a generator
to serve a neighborhood.

00:48:00.610 --> 00:48:02.880
And then maybe you go
to alternating current.

00:48:02.880 --> 00:48:07.170
But technically, once you
can do higher voltages,

00:48:07.170 --> 00:48:09.120
you can expand.

00:48:09.120 --> 00:48:11.760
You can link up separate cities.

00:48:11.760 --> 00:48:14.730
And that began to
happen after the turn

00:48:14.730 --> 00:48:20.460
of the century and states took
over-regulation from cities.

00:48:20.460 --> 00:48:24.620
The idea was we'd set up
these impartial commissions.

00:48:24.620 --> 00:48:27.980
And these impartial
non-political public utility

00:48:27.980 --> 00:48:34.220
commissions, not elected in most
states, not subject to removal

00:48:34.220 --> 00:48:35.970
by the government,
independent commissions

00:48:35.970 --> 00:48:39.970
was an invention that
started, I'm now forgetting,

00:48:39.970 --> 00:48:41.910
I think Wisconsin in 1907.

00:48:41.910 --> 00:48:45.400
And by 1920, everybody,
almost everybody had them.

00:48:45.400 --> 00:48:46.650
Is anybody here from Nebraska?

00:48:49.400 --> 00:48:52.640
OK, Nebraska doesn't have
a public utility commission

00:48:52.640 --> 00:48:55.430
because no private
firm is selling

00:48:55.430 --> 00:48:56.990
electricity in Nebraska.

00:48:56.990 --> 00:48:59.000
It's all government and co-ops.

00:48:59.000 --> 00:49:02.130
But everybody else has one.

00:49:02.130 --> 00:49:05.040
The Europeans didn't do this.

00:49:05.040 --> 00:49:08.490
What happened, the European
system started out like this.

00:49:08.490 --> 00:49:13.590
It started out
local, began to grow

00:49:13.590 --> 00:49:17.080
and became government
enterprises.

00:49:17.080 --> 00:49:17.580
Why?

00:49:24.980 --> 00:49:28.130
OK, you figure that's the answer
to an engineering question.

00:49:30.710 --> 00:49:33.910
That is not the answer to
an engineering question.

00:49:33.910 --> 00:49:37.470
The same electrons,
same technology,

00:49:37.470 --> 00:49:39.480
similar densities in many areas.

00:49:39.480 --> 00:49:41.678
Jacob, save me here.

00:49:41.678 --> 00:49:43.470
AUDIENCE: Although they
may have provinces,

00:49:43.470 --> 00:49:46.110
they're not as independent
government institutions

00:49:46.110 --> 00:49:47.830
as they are in
the United States.

00:49:47.830 --> 00:49:51.460
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Well,
that's true to some extent.

00:49:51.460 --> 00:49:54.350
Although, take Germany.

00:49:54.350 --> 00:49:58.668
Germany is and has been to
the extent that it was--

00:49:58.668 --> 00:50:00.460
well, it wasn't democratic
for a long time.

00:50:00.460 --> 00:50:03.868
But it began as a set
of independent countries

00:50:03.868 --> 00:50:05.035
that became the [INAUDIBLE].

00:50:05.035 --> 00:50:07.760
It became a federal system.

00:50:07.760 --> 00:50:14.050
So when the government took
over the Berlin system,

00:50:14.050 --> 00:50:15.610
it was the Berlin government.

00:50:15.610 --> 00:50:18.410
It wasn't the
national government.

00:50:18.410 --> 00:50:21.233
So not all of these government
enterprises were national.

00:50:21.233 --> 00:50:22.150
But it's a good point.

00:50:22.150 --> 00:50:23.567
The political
structures differed.

00:50:23.567 --> 00:50:26.440
And the US was if
not unique, then

00:50:26.440 --> 00:50:29.920
it stood out as having
this whole state structure.

00:50:32.810 --> 00:50:35.810
It's just an
ideological difference.

00:50:35.810 --> 00:50:37.160
An ideological difference.

00:50:37.160 --> 00:50:40.490
The US had a strong preference
for private enterprise.

00:50:40.490 --> 00:50:42.690
Europe had a less
strong preference.

00:50:47.990 --> 00:50:51.110
It was a big debate in
the US through the '30s.

00:50:51.110 --> 00:50:54.356
Should this stuff be government
or should it be private?

00:50:54.356 --> 00:50:56.550
Private mostly won in the US.

00:50:56.550 --> 00:50:59.880
Government mostly won in Europe.

00:50:59.880 --> 00:51:02.640
You can make
arguments both ways.

00:51:02.640 --> 00:51:06.570
I talked about various
solutions to natural monopolies.

00:51:06.570 --> 00:51:08.940
The government
solution is, look,

00:51:08.940 --> 00:51:11.730
there are no shareholders
trying to rape and pillage here.

00:51:11.730 --> 00:51:14.580
We're just all trying
to serve the customers.

00:51:14.580 --> 00:51:17.010
The private response
is, yes, and you're all

00:51:17.010 --> 00:51:18.630
hiring your brother-in-laws.

00:51:18.630 --> 00:51:20.460
The costs are high.

00:51:20.460 --> 00:51:22.530
You have no stockholder
pressure to be efficient.

00:51:22.530 --> 00:51:23.940
Costs will be too high.

00:51:23.940 --> 00:51:26.700
That debate ran
for 30, 40 years.

00:51:26.700 --> 00:51:29.320
It still goes on
in some quarters.

00:51:29.320 --> 00:51:30.420
One side won in Europe.

00:51:30.420 --> 00:51:31.530
One side won in the US.

00:51:35.160 --> 00:51:40.730
OK, so far the
states, now the feds.

00:51:40.730 --> 00:51:45.650
The federal government got
into electricity first in 1906

00:51:45.650 --> 00:51:50.030
selling cheap surplus power
from irrigation projects.

00:51:50.030 --> 00:51:52.760
It gave preference to
municipalities rather than

00:51:52.760 --> 00:51:54.540
private buyers.

00:51:54.540 --> 00:51:56.418
Why was it cheap, do you think?

00:51:56.418 --> 00:51:58.460
Why was the power cheap
from irrigation projects?

00:52:01.390 --> 00:52:05.380
OK, today is quirky
political explanations day.

00:52:05.380 --> 00:52:08.710
In calculating the cost
of building something,

00:52:08.710 --> 00:52:11.950
the government tends to
use its borrowing rate.

00:52:11.950 --> 00:52:13.630
The cost of capital
to the government,

00:52:13.630 --> 00:52:17.290
which has the power to tax is
lower than the cost of capital

00:52:17.290 --> 00:52:19.790
to private firms that don't.

00:52:19.790 --> 00:52:22.310
So all else equal,
the government

00:52:22.310 --> 00:52:23.960
can produce power cheaper.

00:52:23.960 --> 00:52:25.910
And if the main cost
is capital, which

00:52:25.910 --> 00:52:30.030
it is for a hydro facility,
it could be a lot cheaper.

00:52:30.030 --> 00:52:32.360
So the government says,
we're not making any money,

00:52:32.360 --> 00:52:34.010
we will sell it cheaply.

00:52:34.010 --> 00:52:36.020
But then you've got to
figure out who gets it.

00:52:36.020 --> 00:52:38.090
And the decision was
municipal utilities.

00:52:41.960 --> 00:52:44.540
During the run up to the '20s--

00:52:44.540 --> 00:52:46.170
and that's an
amazing period if you

00:52:46.170 --> 00:52:47.420
think about growth industries.

00:52:47.420 --> 00:52:48.860
I just ran the numbers.

00:52:48.860 --> 00:52:51.830
The growth in electric
power between 1900 and 1929

00:52:51.830 --> 00:52:54.290
averaged 14% a year.

00:52:54.290 --> 00:52:55.430
That's a boom.

00:52:55.430 --> 00:52:57.350
That's a long boom.

00:52:57.350 --> 00:52:59.420
That was fun.

00:52:59.420 --> 00:53:02.390
It was fun except that these
guys were being regulated.

00:53:02.390 --> 00:53:06.890
So their response was, we're
being regulated by states.

00:53:06.890 --> 00:53:10.920
Let's have holding companies
that operate in multiple states

00:53:10.920 --> 00:53:15.650
so we can kind of hide
the ball from regulators.

00:53:15.650 --> 00:53:19.520
And it was used to
fuel stock speculation.

00:53:19.520 --> 00:53:20.720
So they had a lot of fun.

00:53:20.720 --> 00:53:24.580
They built these big
holding companies.

00:53:24.580 --> 00:53:25.600
I'll come back to that.

00:53:25.600 --> 00:53:28.510
The federal power
commission, now the FERC,

00:53:28.510 --> 00:53:31.900
was formed in 1920 because
all navigable waterways

00:53:31.900 --> 00:53:32.980
are federal.

00:53:32.980 --> 00:53:37.160
It began to do some
regulation from 1935.

00:53:37.160 --> 00:53:40.610
In 1935 in response to
these holding companies,

00:53:40.610 --> 00:53:43.910
which really were
weird creatures.

00:53:43.910 --> 00:53:47.270
And they were blamed for the
stock market crash of 1929.

00:53:47.270 --> 00:53:49.295
You always need to
find a scapegoat.

00:53:49.295 --> 00:53:51.170
So the scapegoat was
these utility companies.

00:53:51.170 --> 00:53:51.878
They were broken.

00:53:51.878 --> 00:53:52.790
They were broken up.

00:53:52.790 --> 00:53:56.083
You had to operate in
one contiguous area.

00:53:56.083 --> 00:53:58.250
You couldn't have a company
here and a company there

00:53:58.250 --> 00:53:59.760
under the same umbrella.

00:53:59.760 --> 00:54:04.400
Well, that really enforced what
was the vertically integrated

00:54:04.400 --> 00:54:05.327
monopoly structure.

00:54:05.327 --> 00:54:07.910
The same company would generate
the power, transmit the power,

00:54:07.910 --> 00:54:08.930
and sell you the power.

00:54:12.740 --> 00:54:19.140
In the '30s, one of
Roosevelt's initiatives

00:54:19.140 --> 00:54:23.250
was to get power to rural
areas, one of his priorities.

00:54:23.250 --> 00:54:26.280
The existing utilities
weren't interested in doing it

00:54:26.280 --> 00:54:29.210
because it's expensive.

00:54:29.210 --> 00:54:31.580
And their current
customers didn't

00:54:31.580 --> 00:54:34.250
want to pay higher prices so
the farmer in the next county

00:54:34.250 --> 00:54:37.240
can get power.

00:54:37.240 --> 00:54:42.900
What the federal remedy was,
we'll enable a set of co-ops.

00:54:42.900 --> 00:54:47.455
And we'll sell them cheap
power from federal facilities.

00:54:47.455 --> 00:54:48.330
That's what was done.

00:54:48.330 --> 00:54:50.730
TVA is the most
visible sort of we'll

00:54:50.730 --> 00:54:53.490
generate from federal
facilities and sell cheap.

00:54:53.490 --> 00:54:56.880
But we did a bunch of it.

00:54:56.880 --> 00:55:01.080
And in 1950 when it peaked,
the federal government

00:55:01.080 --> 00:55:07.660
generated 12% of
us electricity, OK.

00:55:07.660 --> 00:55:09.220
So far so good?

00:55:09.220 --> 00:55:10.060
That's the history.

00:55:13.260 --> 00:55:26.080
State regulation-- so the
bulk of the regulatory effort

00:55:26.080 --> 00:55:31.020
from 1907, particularly
after 1935, that's PUHCA,

00:55:31.020 --> 00:55:34.370
always pronounced puka.

00:55:34.370 --> 00:55:39.260
State regulators required
just and reasonable rates.

00:55:39.260 --> 00:55:42.350
This was rate of
return regulation.

00:55:42.350 --> 00:55:45.410
They would set
prices in principle

00:55:45.410 --> 00:55:49.697
so that the utility would just
earn a fair rate of return.

00:55:49.697 --> 00:55:51.030
You've got to have some profits.

00:55:51.030 --> 00:55:51.740
What's a fair profit?

00:55:51.740 --> 00:55:53.180
Well, we know what your
cost of capital is.

00:55:53.180 --> 00:55:54.770
We'll figure out what that is.

00:55:54.770 --> 00:55:58.980
And we'll set the rates
so you just earn that.

00:55:58.980 --> 00:56:03.100
So what might go wrong?

00:56:11.580 --> 00:56:14.760
Alex, Shirley you're about
to raise your hand now.

00:56:14.760 --> 00:56:17.010
I keep watching
this hand going--

00:56:17.010 --> 00:56:17.760
What do you think?

00:56:17.760 --> 00:56:18.600
What could go wrong?

00:56:18.600 --> 00:56:19.100
Anything?

00:56:23.450 --> 00:56:26.750
We're going to set prices
so that you just earn

00:56:26.750 --> 00:56:30.062
a reasonable rate of return.

00:56:30.062 --> 00:56:34.710
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
what that is.

00:56:34.710 --> 00:56:37.770
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
You can get it wrong.

00:56:37.770 --> 00:56:39.300
We'll set a price.

00:56:39.300 --> 00:56:42.540
And we'll let it.

00:56:42.540 --> 00:56:46.500
Well, we'll set a price and
let's suppose we adjust it

00:56:46.500 --> 00:56:48.180
when we get surprises.

00:56:48.180 --> 00:56:50.220
Or let's say, we
are worried about,

00:56:50.220 --> 00:56:52.500
and this is what they
did do after a while.

00:56:52.500 --> 00:56:55.680
We know that you can't
control your cost of fuel.

00:56:55.680 --> 00:56:57.130
That's on the open market.

00:56:57.130 --> 00:57:01.270
So we'll pass that
through automatically.

00:57:01.270 --> 00:57:02.193
Anything else?

00:57:02.193 --> 00:57:04.360
Anything else that could
go wrong if I make sure you

00:57:04.360 --> 00:57:06.310
just earn a reasonable
rate of return?

00:57:10.220 --> 00:57:12.400
OK, let me not torture
you, think about it.

00:57:12.400 --> 00:57:13.203
Yes.

00:57:13.203 --> 00:57:14.870
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
the variable cost.

00:57:14.870 --> 00:57:18.510
They have no incentive
to try to be efficient.

00:57:18.510 --> 00:57:19.910
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
So you would

00:57:19.910 --> 00:57:24.230
expect the big problem
would be that the cost would

00:57:24.230 --> 00:57:25.940
be too high.

00:57:25.940 --> 00:57:29.720
Suppose-- and we can even
sharpen that a little bit.

00:57:29.720 --> 00:57:35.450
And that is the main defect
in that form of regulation.

00:57:35.450 --> 00:57:38.790
Suppose we recognize
the following.

00:57:38.790 --> 00:57:41.150
If I say that a
reasonable rate of return

00:57:41.150 --> 00:57:46.450
is below your cost of capital,
then you can't function, right?

00:57:46.450 --> 00:57:49.210
If you can't raise money to
invest because you can't earn

00:57:49.210 --> 00:57:53.060
enough on it, if I've set
the rate of return too low,

00:57:53.060 --> 00:57:54.830
you can't go forward.

00:57:54.830 --> 00:57:56.810
So I don't want that to happen.

00:57:56.810 --> 00:58:00.070
So I make sure you earn more
than your cost of capital

00:58:00.070 --> 00:58:01.450
on the investments.

00:58:01.450 --> 00:58:03.460
I have to make sure that
every dollar you invest

00:58:03.460 --> 00:58:08.720
earns more than what it costs
you to raise that dollar?

00:58:08.720 --> 00:58:12.390
What might that lead
to, just intuitively?

00:58:12.390 --> 00:58:13.290
David.

00:58:13.290 --> 00:58:14.728
AUDIENCE: Over-investment.

00:58:14.728 --> 00:58:16.270
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Over-investment,

00:58:16.270 --> 00:58:19.450
which they referred to in the
literature as gold plating,

00:58:19.450 --> 00:58:19.950
right?

00:58:19.950 --> 00:58:23.710
If I have a choice of doing
it with three people or a $5

00:58:23.710 --> 00:58:26.590
million investment,
I'll do a $5 million

00:58:26.590 --> 00:58:28.900
investment because I'll
earn money on that.

00:58:28.900 --> 00:58:32.160
And I won't earn any
money on the three people.

00:58:32.160 --> 00:58:34.520
So you have a tendency
you would expect to have

00:58:34.520 --> 00:58:38.090
capital investment too high.

00:58:38.090 --> 00:58:40.130
There are a couple
other problems,

00:58:40.130 --> 00:58:41.060
we've hit two of them.

00:58:41.060 --> 00:58:43.730
I'll just mention the others.

00:58:43.730 --> 00:58:46.760
When people talk
about this system,

00:58:46.760 --> 00:58:47.795
they talk about capture.

00:58:51.970 --> 00:58:57.070
Well, I actually gave a talk
at the Massachusetts Commission

00:58:57.070 --> 00:58:58.750
a couple of weeks ago.

00:58:58.750 --> 00:59:02.560
And it turns out
there's a little office

00:59:02.560 --> 00:59:05.140
complex inside South Station.

00:59:05.140 --> 00:59:07.390
You don't see it, but you
kind of go around the corner

00:59:07.390 --> 00:59:11.140
and you go up and they
have some offices.

00:59:11.140 --> 00:59:14.470
Who do you think goes
into those offices?

00:59:14.470 --> 00:59:17.290
The companies they regulate.

00:59:17.290 --> 00:59:22.320
Who do you think says nice
things to them, talks to them,

00:59:22.320 --> 00:59:25.240
has any relationship
with them at all?

00:59:25.240 --> 00:59:28.850
The people they regulate.

00:59:28.850 --> 00:59:31.760
Who has lots of lawyers
and lots of PR people

00:59:31.760 --> 00:59:35.000
to make a lot of noise
if they're unhappy?

00:59:35.000 --> 00:59:37.130
The people they regulate.

00:59:37.130 --> 00:59:42.470
So a strong model not an
entirely accurate model,

00:59:42.470 --> 00:59:46.820
but not an entirely crazy
model is, after a while,

00:59:46.820 --> 00:59:52.520
the regulators serve
the folks they regulate.

00:59:52.520 --> 00:59:54.650
Because you want
to make them happy.

00:59:54.650 --> 00:59:57.830
You see them every day,
they come in your office.

00:59:57.830 --> 00:59:59.840
You can imagine a different
kind of relationship

00:59:59.840 --> 01:00:02.270
and sometimes you see it.

01:00:02.270 --> 01:00:06.230
But one argument is, all the
consumers are not organized.

01:00:06.230 --> 01:00:08.450
The utility is.

01:00:08.450 --> 01:00:10.140
The electric companies
are organized.

01:00:10.140 --> 01:00:10.760
They have the lawyers.

01:00:10.760 --> 01:00:11.630
They have their lobbyists.

01:00:11.630 --> 01:00:12.505
They're in every day.

01:00:12.505 --> 01:00:14.720
They write the stuff.

01:00:14.720 --> 01:00:19.170
Those of us who only pay bills
aren't in there every day.

01:00:19.170 --> 01:00:20.280
So that's one problem.

01:00:20.280 --> 01:00:25.280
The other problem, it's
a more subtle problem is,

01:00:25.280 --> 01:00:29.120
who determines who
pays what price?

01:00:29.120 --> 01:00:32.150
And the simplest example
is, prices to industry

01:00:32.150 --> 01:00:35.550
versus prices to consumers.

01:00:35.550 --> 01:00:37.470
Industry takes power
at higher voltages.

01:00:37.470 --> 01:00:39.450
So they ought to
pay a lower price.

01:00:39.450 --> 01:00:41.128
What's the price difference?

01:00:41.128 --> 01:00:42.920
Well, I submit to you
that price difference

01:00:42.920 --> 01:00:47.450
is a political decision
as much as it is anything.

01:00:47.450 --> 01:00:49.910
And under a regulated
regime, it's

01:00:49.910 --> 01:00:52.310
hard to see how it
could be anything else.

01:00:52.310 --> 01:00:55.840
OK, so this system
actually worked.

01:00:55.840 --> 01:00:57.590
And I'm going to answer
this question just

01:00:57.590 --> 01:01:00.740
in the interest of
our leaving today.

01:01:00.740 --> 01:01:04.610
This system generated almost
no complaints until the 1970s,

01:01:04.610 --> 01:01:08.590
in electric power, despite
all of these well known,

01:01:08.590 --> 01:01:11.190
well-documented problems.

01:01:11.190 --> 01:01:14.280
And the reason for
that is in electricity,

01:01:14.280 --> 01:01:17.260
technical change was very rapid.

01:01:17.260 --> 01:01:19.820
Energy costs were pretty stable.

01:01:19.820 --> 01:01:24.250
And so the price of
electricity was dropping.

01:01:24.250 --> 01:01:26.740
Very often the utility
would come in and ask

01:01:26.740 --> 01:01:29.380
for a rate decrease, all right.

01:01:29.380 --> 01:01:31.840
If you fixed my price, and
my costs keep dropping,

01:01:31.840 --> 01:01:34.210
there comes a point at which
the price is embarrassingly

01:01:34.210 --> 01:01:36.130
high above the monopoly price.

01:01:36.130 --> 01:01:38.110
I'm going to make
me too much money

01:01:38.110 --> 01:01:39.790
to survive political scrutiny.

01:01:39.790 --> 01:01:42.350
I'll ask for a lower price.

01:01:42.350 --> 01:01:44.000
So an awful lot
of that happened.

01:01:44.000 --> 01:01:45.990
That's a great system.

01:01:45.990 --> 01:01:47.550
The regulators don't
have to do much.

01:01:47.550 --> 01:01:50.950
The utility comes in and says,
may we please lower our price.

01:01:50.950 --> 01:01:51.923
We do a big fuss.

01:01:51.923 --> 01:01:52.590
We have lawyers.

01:01:52.590 --> 01:01:56.190
We write briefs, after a while
we say, yeah, lower your price.

01:01:56.190 --> 01:01:57.270
We all go out to lunch.

01:01:57.270 --> 01:01:58.890
This is a good system.

01:01:58.890 --> 01:02:00.900
It didn't work in
the '70s very well

01:02:00.900 --> 01:02:03.535
when fuel costs began to rise.

01:02:03.535 --> 01:02:05.160
And the utilities
came in and said, now

01:02:05.160 --> 01:02:07.390
let us raise our prices.

01:02:07.390 --> 01:02:09.370
And then people began
to say, wait a minute,

01:02:09.370 --> 01:02:10.570
your costs are too high.

01:02:10.570 --> 01:02:12.830
You are gold plated
blah, blah, blah.

01:02:12.830 --> 01:02:14.980
And it began to be nasty.

01:02:14.980 --> 01:02:20.425
OK, so let me take
this up to date.

01:02:23.840 --> 01:02:30.070
In the 1970s, we deregulated a
lot of things in this economy.

01:02:30.070 --> 01:02:31.920
We deregulated airlines.

01:02:31.920 --> 01:02:33.480
We deregulated trucking.

01:02:33.480 --> 01:02:35.280
We deregulated railroads.

01:02:35.280 --> 01:02:39.590
We deregulated the wellhead
price of natural gas.

01:02:39.590 --> 01:02:43.100
And most of those worked.

01:02:43.100 --> 01:02:44.540
Price of natural gas went up.

01:02:44.540 --> 01:02:46.310
But we stopped having shortages.

01:02:46.310 --> 01:02:47.780
Airline prices came down.

01:02:47.780 --> 01:02:49.100
Trucking prices came down.

01:02:49.100 --> 01:02:50.370
Railroad prices came down.

01:02:50.370 --> 01:02:51.410
And costs came down.

01:02:53.960 --> 01:02:57.650
And electricity
prices were going up.

01:02:57.650 --> 01:02:59.660
Fuel costs were going up.

01:02:59.660 --> 01:03:01.320
There was excess capacity.

01:03:01.320 --> 01:03:03.830
People had to pay
for that capacity.

01:03:03.830 --> 01:03:09.290
There became a move to
deregulate electricity.

01:03:09.290 --> 01:03:12.750
But I just told you it
was a natural monopoly.

01:03:12.750 --> 01:03:15.770
So the first step was
this law that said,

01:03:15.770 --> 01:03:17.660
you have to buy from renewables.

01:03:17.660 --> 01:03:20.580
And you have to buy from
combined heat and power

01:03:20.580 --> 01:03:28.050
co-generation, hexion type
units at avoided cost.

01:03:28.050 --> 01:03:29.550
What's avoided cost?

01:03:29.550 --> 01:03:32.100
Well, each state got
to determine that.

01:03:32.100 --> 01:03:34.590
Big mess, there were no markets.

01:03:34.590 --> 01:03:40.200
But an interesting
step, early '80s, and I

01:03:40.200 --> 01:03:43.110
will cite myself here because I
do tend to get cited for this.

01:03:43.110 --> 01:03:45.120
In the early '80s,
Paul Joskow and I

01:03:45.120 --> 01:03:46.540
were working in this area.

01:03:46.540 --> 01:03:50.580
And we began to hear from people
in the Reagan administration,

01:03:50.580 --> 01:03:52.650
all this other stuff worked.

01:03:52.650 --> 01:03:55.860
We deregulated gas and trucking
and airlines, why don't we

01:03:55.860 --> 01:03:58.770
just deregulate electricity.

01:03:58.770 --> 01:04:02.040
Why don't we just let the market
determine electricity prices?

01:04:02.040 --> 01:04:06.690
I have to say, the words
natural monopoly came to mind.

01:04:06.690 --> 01:04:11.100
You're not going to have
competition in transmission.

01:04:11.100 --> 01:04:15.000
You're not going to have
competition in distribution.

01:04:15.000 --> 01:04:19.080
But you know you could have
competition in generation.

01:04:19.080 --> 01:04:20.840
It's not like there's
only one generating

01:04:20.840 --> 01:04:23.450
plant per city or per state.

01:04:23.450 --> 01:04:25.330
There are a bunch of them.

01:04:25.330 --> 01:04:26.570
So maybe you could.

01:04:26.570 --> 01:04:28.790
So we actually wrote a book
called Markets for Power

01:04:28.790 --> 01:04:32.570
that people tell me was
influential more outside the US

01:04:32.570 --> 01:04:34.100
than in.

01:04:34.100 --> 01:04:38.230
But we said well, you could
do it if you were careful.

01:04:38.230 --> 01:04:41.830
If you were careful, and you
worried about market power,

01:04:41.830 --> 01:04:43.977
and you worried about
the proper rules,

01:04:43.977 --> 01:04:46.060
and you worried about a
half a dozen other things,

01:04:46.060 --> 01:04:49.510
you could actually
deregulate generation.

01:04:49.510 --> 01:04:51.250
Well, it happened.

01:04:51.250 --> 01:04:53.410
And I don't claim
credit for this.

01:04:53.410 --> 01:04:56.380
It was mostly because the
Thatcher administration

01:04:56.380 --> 01:04:58.410
in England needed money.

01:04:58.410 --> 01:05:02.370
So they sold the
electric power system.

01:05:02.370 --> 01:05:03.880
This was a shock.

01:05:03.880 --> 01:05:05.780
It had happened in Chile
a few years earlier,

01:05:05.780 --> 01:05:09.440
nobody noticed Chile, besides
they did it in Spanish.

01:05:09.440 --> 01:05:12.470
But in England and
Wales, they did it.

01:05:12.470 --> 01:05:18.050
They kept the grid, the
transmission system together.

01:05:18.050 --> 01:05:20.630
They regulated the
distribution companies,

01:05:20.630 --> 01:05:23.160
but they sold the generators.

01:05:23.160 --> 01:05:24.988
They sold the generators.

01:05:27.680 --> 01:05:29.270
This was pretty exciting stuff.

01:05:29.270 --> 01:05:34.160
And it actually
worked, not perfectly.

01:05:34.160 --> 01:05:37.220
They had monopoly power problems
in generation in some areas.

01:05:37.220 --> 01:05:38.900
They had to make changes.

01:05:38.900 --> 01:05:41.100
But it sort of worked.

01:05:41.100 --> 01:05:42.760
Other countries
started to follow.

01:05:42.760 --> 01:05:46.290
We started to follow.

01:05:46.290 --> 01:05:50.340
Suddenly transmission
lines had to be

01:05:50.340 --> 01:05:52.920
willing to carry anybody's
power from anybody to anybody

01:05:52.920 --> 01:05:55.830
just like trucks do.

01:05:55.830 --> 01:05:59.280
The FERC set up, independent
system operators, they

01:05:59.280 --> 01:06:03.150
set up a regime where you could
have one entity run the system,

01:06:03.150 --> 01:06:05.280
not own it, but run it.

01:06:05.280 --> 01:06:09.360
And you could have wholesale
markets for electricity.

01:06:09.360 --> 01:06:12.390
Some people did it, and
I'll show you what happened.

01:06:12.390 --> 01:06:15.130
Then we had California.

01:06:15.130 --> 01:06:17.520
Who's from California?

01:06:17.520 --> 01:06:19.300
Was that fun?

01:06:19.300 --> 01:06:20.770
That was not fun.

01:06:20.770 --> 01:06:25.270
Prices went crazy in
California, around 2000, 2001.

01:06:25.270 --> 01:06:26.980
There were blackouts.

01:06:26.980 --> 01:06:28.210
There was screaming.

01:06:28.210 --> 01:06:29.500
There was political crisis.

01:06:29.500 --> 01:06:32.840
There was Enron doing
various interesting things.

01:06:32.840 --> 01:06:36.820
There's litigation, which
may now have finished.

01:06:36.820 --> 01:06:46.227
I'm not sure about who did
what to whom, reform stopped.

01:06:46.227 --> 01:06:47.560
We'll say a little bit about it.

01:06:47.560 --> 01:06:52.230
But let me just say
sort of where we are.

01:06:52.230 --> 01:06:54.660
So basically nothing's
happened since California

01:06:54.660 --> 01:06:56.460
to a first approximation.

01:06:56.460 --> 01:06:59.580
But a lot happened
before California.

01:06:59.580 --> 01:07:04.980
So there is competition
in generation.

01:07:04.980 --> 01:07:06.480
Generators sell into a market.

01:07:09.460 --> 01:07:13.600
In England and Wales, it's the
core European Union policy.

01:07:13.600 --> 01:07:16.600
All these state owned monopolies
are moving toward markets,

01:07:16.600 --> 01:07:18.580
dramatically, dramatically.

01:07:18.580 --> 01:07:21.160
And about 2/3 of US consumers
are served by markets.

01:07:21.160 --> 01:07:23.170
This is the picture.

01:07:23.170 --> 01:07:25.480
The colored areas are roughly--

01:07:25.480 --> 01:07:27.550
they change slightly over time--

01:07:27.550 --> 01:07:31.700
roughly the boundaries of
organized wholesale markets.

01:07:31.700 --> 01:07:33.880
So in New England, I
showed you these day

01:07:33.880 --> 01:07:35.950
ahead clearing demands.

01:07:35.950 --> 01:07:39.340
And I'll show you some
prices in a little bit.

01:07:39.340 --> 01:07:43.090
This part of Texas runs
a very nice market.

01:07:43.090 --> 01:07:47.650
California after
a while restarted.

01:07:47.650 --> 01:07:51.070
This part of the country
is traditional, vertically

01:07:51.070 --> 01:07:52.190
integrated.

01:07:52.190 --> 01:07:52.870
We generate.

01:07:52.870 --> 01:07:53.590
We transmit.

01:07:53.590 --> 01:07:54.340
We distribute.

01:07:54.340 --> 01:07:57.340
What's a market utilities.

01:07:57.340 --> 01:08:01.270
In the West, the federal
government has a huge presence,

01:08:01.270 --> 01:08:05.260
operates a lot of the
transmission system.

01:08:05.260 --> 01:08:07.600
There are sort of elements
of market, but not really.

01:08:07.600 --> 01:08:09.580
And there's an awful
lot of preference power.

01:08:09.580 --> 01:08:12.320
Because there's a lot of
government-owned hydro.

01:08:12.320 --> 01:08:15.230
If you go up the Columbia
River, you pass a dam after dam

01:08:15.230 --> 01:08:19.960
after dam which you all own.

01:08:19.960 --> 01:08:23.710
So New England, one
of the earlier ones,

01:08:23.710 --> 01:08:27.439
very nice little market.

01:08:27.439 --> 01:08:29.950
These are average
wholesale prices

01:08:29.950 --> 01:08:34.000
in New England
for the last year.

01:08:34.000 --> 01:08:37.200
The prices are hourly I think.

01:08:37.200 --> 01:08:38.950
Maybe they've gone
down to 15 minutes now.

01:08:38.950 --> 01:08:40.450
But at least hourly.

01:08:40.450 --> 01:08:44.870
They also are
differentiated by region.

01:08:44.870 --> 01:08:47.990
If there's a problem
transmitting power from A to B,

01:08:47.990 --> 01:08:50.870
the prices in A
and B can differ.

01:08:50.870 --> 01:08:53.990
If there is no problem,
they differ trivially.

01:08:53.990 --> 01:08:56.540
So again, this is
the day ahead price,

01:08:56.540 --> 01:08:58.069
and this is the real time price.

01:09:01.399 --> 01:09:05.149
I don't know what happened
last August, or late July,

01:09:05.149 --> 01:09:07.580
whether that was a
particularly hot day.

01:09:07.580 --> 01:09:10.270
It was clearly anticipated.

01:09:10.270 --> 01:09:15.620
You see the blue shot
up as well as the green.

01:09:15.620 --> 01:09:17.390
Sometimes the day
ahead is too high.

01:09:17.390 --> 01:09:19.670
Sometimes the day
ahead is too low.

01:09:19.670 --> 01:09:21.319
There is a day ahead market.

01:09:21.319 --> 01:09:23.510
And then there is
what actually has

01:09:23.510 --> 01:09:25.620
to happen to follow the load.

01:09:25.620 --> 01:09:31.370
So sometimes the day
ahead market overestimates

01:09:31.370 --> 01:09:32.899
demand and thus costs.

01:09:32.899 --> 01:09:34.580
Sometimes it underestimates.

01:09:34.580 --> 01:09:39.649
But those are daily prices.

01:09:39.649 --> 01:09:45.710
I'll show you some
hourly prices on Monday.

01:09:45.710 --> 01:09:49.010
And here's what
the US looks like.

01:09:49.010 --> 01:09:50.930
No other country
has a system that

01:09:50.930 --> 01:09:55.390
is this fragmented and diverse,
with the possible exception

01:09:55.390 --> 01:09:57.790
of Japan depending on how
you count fragmentation

01:09:57.790 --> 01:10:00.940
and diversity,
since half of Japan

01:10:00.940 --> 01:10:03.220
runs on 50 cycles a
second and half of Japan

01:10:03.220 --> 01:10:05.630
runs on 60 cycles.

01:10:05.630 --> 01:10:08.230
We at least beat that.

01:10:08.230 --> 01:10:13.210
So about 2/3 are served
by organized markets.

01:10:13.210 --> 01:10:15.400
ISO is Independent
System Operator,

01:10:15.400 --> 01:10:18.400
RTO is Regional
Transmission Operator.

01:10:18.400 --> 01:10:21.200
Differences are immaterial.

01:10:21.200 --> 01:10:23.020
We have a transmission
system owned

01:10:23.020 --> 01:10:27.700
by about 450 different entities,
some federal, some local,

01:10:27.700 --> 01:10:29.770
some state, some private.

01:10:29.770 --> 01:10:35.660
About 2/3 of the system
is owned by private firms.

01:10:35.660 --> 01:10:40.880
We have on the order
of 3,200 entities

01:10:40.880 --> 01:10:48.020
selling electricity, 3,200
entities selling electricity.

01:10:48.020 --> 01:10:50.090
Cooperatives aren't
regulated by anybody.

01:10:50.090 --> 01:10:53.360
Investor owned utilities,
which are about 2/3

01:10:53.360 --> 01:10:56.150
regulated by states and by feds.

01:10:56.150 --> 01:10:57.890
The munis and the
federal systems

01:10:57.890 --> 01:11:00.530
are not regulated by anybody.

01:11:00.530 --> 01:11:05.270
And that retail
competitors at the bottom

01:11:05.270 --> 01:11:08.585
is a development that was
under way before California.

01:11:08.585 --> 01:11:13.310
It has gotten stalled
because of California.

01:11:13.310 --> 01:11:18.530
But in Texas is where
it's most prevalent.

01:11:18.530 --> 01:11:22.100
You can buy electricity
from any one

01:11:22.100 --> 01:11:23.750
of a number of competing firms.

01:11:23.750 --> 01:11:28.670
It will be delivered by the
monopoly distribution company.

01:11:28.670 --> 01:11:31.400
But you will pay for it
to some other firm that's

01:11:31.400 --> 01:11:34.610
responsible for making sure
there's enough electricity

01:11:34.610 --> 01:11:36.360
to serve its customers.

01:11:36.360 --> 01:11:38.540
That's the model in Europe.

01:11:38.540 --> 01:11:43.850
It exists in Massachusetts,
but isn't very effective.

01:11:43.850 --> 01:11:46.580
Just last week I got
my first solicitation--

01:11:46.580 --> 01:11:48.320
this has been 10 years--

01:11:48.320 --> 01:11:50.030
to switch suppliers.

01:11:50.030 --> 01:11:53.120
And because I believe
in computation, I did.

01:11:53.120 --> 01:11:54.950
So there's enough
retail competition

01:11:54.950 --> 01:11:57.820
that people who
don't own wires--

01:11:57.820 --> 01:11:59.570
plus I thought I'd see
what would happen--

01:11:59.570 --> 01:12:04.550
plus people who don't own wires
sold 8% of the electricity

01:12:04.550 --> 01:12:06.440
in the country.

01:12:06.440 --> 01:12:08.930
I think these are 2010 numbers.

01:12:08.930 --> 01:12:10.880
That's a big change.

01:12:10.880 --> 01:12:12.560
That was 0.

01:12:12.560 --> 01:12:16.850
The bigger change is
on the generation side.

01:12:16.850 --> 01:12:18.920
So you have government systems--

01:12:18.920 --> 01:12:22.100
and this is a big number, 16%.

01:12:22.100 --> 01:12:25.610
Not all federal, some
state, some municipal,

01:12:25.610 --> 01:12:28.070
Los Angeles for instance, 16%.

01:12:28.070 --> 01:12:30.080
Investor owned utilities
with retail sales,

01:12:30.080 --> 01:12:33.530
42%, independent
producers, folks

01:12:33.530 --> 01:12:37.040
who have entered the wholesale
market who do not sell directly

01:12:37.040 --> 01:12:40.700
to retail customers
42% of generation.

01:12:40.700 --> 01:12:43.460
So we have moved
a fairly long way

01:12:43.460 --> 01:12:45.870
toward a market based system.

01:12:45.870 --> 01:12:48.200
But we're not quite there.